1. Binary Classification with Logistic Regression  
   1. The binary classification using logistic regression yielded strong results by leveraging linear decision boundaries to distinguish between normal and unhealthy lung X-rays. For this binary classification, a linear classifier is used to distinguish whether the X-rays are 0, normal, or 1, unhealthy.Unhealthy cases include COVID-19, pneumonia, and other infections, which shows distinct visual differences from normal lung images. For this task, normal lung X-rays were labeled as 0 and unhealthy ones as 1\. Since the dataset had a significantly higher number of unhealthy X-rays, an undersampling method was applied to balance the training data and prevent bias toward the majority class. To mitigate overfitting, cross-validation was used with randomized train-test splits, which is one of the given helper functions. The data is splitted into 8 to 2 ratios where the size of the training dataset is larger than the testing dataset. Before training the data, the new training dataset, the balanced training dataset, is normalized. The pixel sizes are resized to 128 by 128 in order to run without RAM clashes.   
      The model performed consistently across all three types of unhealthy lungs, achieving an accuracy of 78.8% on the training set and 77.0% on the testing set. Beyond accuracy, the ROC curve showed strong performance with an AUC of 0.849 (where 1 is ideal). Precision and recall scores were \[0.761, 0.779\] and \[0.769, 0.771\], respectively, resulting in F1 scores of \[0.765, 0.775\]. These metrics indicate that the model classified all types of unhealthy lungs effectively and maintained a balanced performance.

2. Other Binary Classifier  
   1. To compare with logistic regression, a K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) classifier was also applied for binary classification. Unlike logistic regression, KNN does not rely on a loss function, yet it satisfies the requirements for binary classification. The KNN model was used to predict the testing dataset with the number of neighbors set to 5\.  
      As previously noted, the dataset is imbalanced, with significantly more normal lung X-rays than unhealthy ones. To address this, the same undersampled dataset was used, where both normal and unhealthy lung X-rays are equally represented in the training set. Specifically, stacked\_data contained an equal number of samples from each class, and stacked\_labels reflected this balance. The same cross-validation strategy from the logistic regression experiment was applied here as well.  
      The KNN classifier achieved an accuracy of 83%, an F1 score of 0.837, and an AUC of 0.833, indicating strong overall performance. The model effectively classified lung X-rays into two categories: 0 for normal and 1 for unhealthy, demonstrating its capability in binary classification. Compared to binary classification with logistic regression, it performed better in the sense of accuracy, but binary classification with logistic regression performed better in ROC. This shows that the KNN is slightly more biased toward the majority class than the binary classification with logistic regression, but it is not really a meaningful amount.

      (Result of 25 lung x-rays, 100 x-rays are printed on the notebook)  
   2.  The third binary classification approach applied was a Decision Tree model. Similar to the previous two methods, the dataset was imbalanced, with significantly more normal lung X-rays than unhealthy ones. To address this, the same undersampled dataset was used, and cross-validated data ensured consistency across experiments.  
      As shown below, the Decision Tree model achieved an accuracy of 75%, an F1 score of 0.77, and an AUC of 0.82, all strong performance indicators. Additional metrics further support this, including a precision of \[0.767, 0.741\], recall of \[0.708, 0.795\], and F1 scores of \[0.737, 0.767\] for each class.  
      Due to the high dimensionality of the dataset and the computational demands of Decision Trees, Principal Component Analysis (PCA) was applied to reduce dimensionality and prevent runtime crashes. This significantly improved execution speed without compromising performance.  
      When comparing all three binary classification models, each demonstrated distinct advantages and trade-offs:  
      K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) showed the strongest performance metrics in this specific case but was computationally inefficient for larger datasets and sensitive to the choice of k.  
      Logistic Regression offered a good balance of performance and interpretability, making it well-suited for scenarios where simplicity is valued. However, it underperformed compared to KNN, likely due to its inability to capture complex, non-linear patterns.  
      Decision Trees, like Logistic Regression, are easy to interpret but require careful parameter tuning to avoid overfitting. The use of PCA was essential in this case to manage resource constraints during training.  
        
3. Specific Diagnosis Classification  
   1. The multi-layer neural network developed for classifying lung radiographs into four categories COVID-19, viral pneumonia, non-COVID(other) infection, and normal demonstrated strong performance, achieving 81.1% accuracy on the training set and 78.5% on the test set. This indicates the model's ability to generalize effectively to unseen data.  
      Class distribution across the four categories was imbalanced, a similar method used for previous classification is used in order to balance the dataset. This balance ensured that the model did not develop a bias toward any particular class, contributing to more equitable classification performance.  
      A train-test split or cross-validation was used to evaluate the model’s generalization and prevent overfitting. When overfitting signs emerged, batch normalization was introduced. This technique stabilized and accelerated the learning process by normalizing layer inputs for each mini-batch, ultimately improving the model’s robustness and training efficiency.  
      The use of CrossEntropyLoss was appropriate for this multi-class classification task. It integrates LogSoftmax and negative log-likelihood loss into a single formulation, making it well-suited to handle the raw, unnormalized outputs from the final layer of the model.  
      In terms of feature representation, the model processed flattened raw pixel values from resized images. This resizing acted as a form of dimensionality reduction, helping manage memory consumption. Additionally, incorporating multi-layer neural networks further improved performance by enabling the model to learn spatial patterns more effectively.  
      In summary, the neural network architecture was well-aligned with the task, balancing complexity and generalization. It did perform better than the binary classification models that were created before multi-linear, but not very significant. This is because for binary classification, there are only two categories which is only consider either healthy or unhealthy, but for this multi-layer classification, unhealthy lung X-rays need to be classified.

   2. Based on the confusion matrix I created, I could find the 3 most common misclassifications. The top 3 misclassifications from the confusion matrix are the one that is predicted 0, but actually 3, with the confusion matrix value of 0.13. The second one predicts class 3 where it is actually 1 with the confusion matrix value of 0.13. Lastly, the one predicted class 1 that is actually 0 with the confusion matrix of 0.08.  
      The first misclassification (3 but predicted 0 with 0.13) was misclassified because the lungs look reasonably clear with little visible abnormal opacity, which may have led the model to incorrectly classify it as normal.   
      The second misclassification (1 but predicted 3 with 0.13) was misclassified because the radiograph has a noticeable annotation and is lower in contrast. Both COVID-19 and viral pneumonia can present with bilateral opacities or similar patterns (according to Google Research).  
      The last misclassification (0 but predicted 1 with 0.08) was misclassified because the lungs appear clear and symmetrical with no obvious signs of color changes, which could be the reason why the model predicted as “normal.”
